# Branching & Deploy Workflow – Sleepfactor Website

## Overview

The Sleepfactor marketing website uses a **development branch workflow** so you can test changes (e.g. via Vercel previews) before they go live. Production is deployed by Vercel from the `main` branch.

- **development** – Where all day-to-day changes and commits go. Use this for testing.
- **main** – Production. Only updated by merging from `development` (e.g. via a pull request) after you’re happy with tests.

## Rule for Commits and Pushes

**When working in the SleepfactorWebsite repo:**

- **Always commit and push to the `development` branch** unless the user explicitly asks to merge to `main`, open a PR to `main`, or work directly on `main`.
- Before committing or pushing, switch to `development` (e.g. `git checkout development` or `git switch development`). If `development` doesn’t exist yet, create it from `main` and push it once.
- Do **not** push directly to `main` unless the user has explicitly asked you to do so (e.g. “push to main” or “merge to main”).

This keeps production (`main`) updated only after you’ve tested on `development` and merged.

## Workflow Summary

| Step | Branch | What happens |
|------|--------|----------------|
| 1. Make changes | development | Edit files, commit, push to `origin development`. |
| 2. Test | Vercel preview | Use the Vercel preview URL for `development` (or for a PR) to test the site. |
| 3. Release | PR → main | When tests pass, open a Pull Request from `development` into `main` on GitHub and merge. |
| 4. Deploy | main | Vercel deploys from `main` to your production URL. |

## Commands (for reference)

```bash
# Ensure you're on development (create it from main if needed)
git checkout development
# or, first time: git checkout -b development && git push -u origin development

# After making changes: commit and push to development
git add .
git commit -m "Description of changes"
git push origin development
```

To update production: open a PR **development → main** on GitHub, review, then merge. Vercel will deploy `main`.

## GitHub Setup (one-time)

For extra safety, you can protect `main` so it can’t be pushed to directly:

- **GitHub repo → Settings → Branches → Add branch protection rule** for `main`.
- Enable **“Require a pull request before merging”** (and any status checks if you add them later).

Then all updates to `main` go through a PR from `development`.

